'''Romeo Alexander Horton''' (1923–2005) was an [[Americo-Liberian]] businessman and civil servant.{{Efn|name=Americo|Horton disputed the label Americo-Liberian and referred to himself as Liberian.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=YYKAAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA21&dq=%22Romeo+Horton%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwja8LnJh_LdAhWD2YMKHQeWBCMQ6AEIPTAF#v=onepage&q=%22Romeo%20Horton%22&f=false|title=The Nobody Manifesto & You|last=MD|first=Lawrence Zumo|date=2013-09-30|publisher=AuthorHouse|isbn=9781491820773|language=en}}</ref>}}
== Early life == Romeo Horton was born to Reverend Daniel Horton and Ora Milner Horton on August 20, 1923 in [[Monrovia, Liberia]]. Horton began his education at the [[Ricks Institute]] in [[Virginia]] under the tutelage of his father who was principal. Hortons's father transferred to the [[Booker Washington Institute]] (specifically to the Agriculture Department) and Horton also enrolled there and graduated his eighth grade class in 1937. Horton graduated from [[Morehouse College]] in [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=9kIDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA24&lpg=PA24&dq=%22Romeo+A.+Horton%22&source=bl&ots=hTjPJGwwzj&sig=BmaXZ005Kxsz_cXr9OckYvb1gNE&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwifk4KehPLdAhWn7YMKHYUhCicQ6AEwC3oECAEQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Romeo%20A.%20Horton%22&f=false|title=Jet|last=Company|first=Johnson Publishing|date=1976-11-11|publisher=Johnson Publishing Company|language=en}}</ref>
== Professional career == As a businessman, he was the founder and former president of the [[Central Bank of Liberia]]. He briefly served as the president of [[Liberia National Airlines]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=vVr8AAAAQBAJ&pg=PA107&lpg=PA107&dq=%22Romeo+A.+Horton%22&source=bl&ots=cq8TNmrU3W&sig=TDhzOYK2CnMjIZGwSthw5dKc7Mw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwifk4KehPLdAhWn7YMKHYUhCicQ6AEwCnoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Romeo%20A.%20Horton%22&f=false|title=Encyclopedia of African Airlines|last=Guttery|first=Ben R.|date=1998|publisher=Ben Guttery|isbn=9780786404957|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=JXgpAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Romeo+A.+Horton%22&dq=%22Romeo+A.+Horton%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiVseC1hvLdAhWsz4MKHQTbCnAQ6AEIODAE|title=Aeroplane and Commercial Aviation News|date=1965|language=en}}</ref>
As a civil servant, he was the assistant economic advisor to [[William Tubman]], the 19th president of [[Liberia]], before he was promoted to [[first Secretary of Commerce, Industry and Labor]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=i7kDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA53&dq=%22Romeo+Horton%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwja8LnJh_LdAhWD2YMKHQeWBCMQ6AEILzAC#v=onepage&q=%22Romeo%20Horton%22&f=false|title=Jet|last=Company|first=Johnson Publishing|date=1965-10-21|publisher=Johnson Publishing Company|language=en}}</ref> He was the chairman of the [[Liberia Elections Support Group]] and the managing director of the [[Economic Community of West African States]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=yXLxAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Romeo+Horton%22&dq=%22Romeo+Horton%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiqk66wjPLdAhXs44MKHTkcBlY4ChDoAQgqMAE|title=West African Journal|date=1991|publisher=Mualay Entertainment Communications|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=1BXoOlgYZY8C&q=%22Romeo+Horton%22&dq=%22Romeo+Horton%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiqk66wjPLdAhXs44MKHTkcBlY4ChDoAQgtMAI|title=Congressional Record: Proceedings and Debates of the ... Congress|date=1978|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|language=en}}</ref> He was one of the founders of the [[African Development Bank]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=07sDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA46&dq=%22Romeo+Horton%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwja8LnJh_LdAhWD2YMKHQeWBCMQ6AEIKzAB#v=onepage&q=%22Romeo%20Horton%22&f=false|title=Jet|last=Company|first=Johnson Publishing|date=1962-11-22|publisher=Johnson Publishing Company|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?redir_esc=y&id=seTnAgAAQBAJ&q=horton#v=snippet&q=horton&f=false|title=Liberia and Independent Africa, 1940s To 2012: A Brief Political Profile|last=Dunn|first=D. Elwood|date=March 2013|publisher=Africana Homestead Legacy Pb|year=|isbn=9781937622510|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>
His memoir, ''For Country, Africa, and My People'' was published in 2004.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=4TGrAAAAIAAJ&q=%22Romeo+Horton%22&dq=%22Romeo+Horton%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwja8LnJh_LdAhWD2YMKHQeWBCMQ6AEIJzAA|title=For Country, Africa, and My People|last=Horton|first=A. Romeo|date=2004|publisher=Ghana Universities Press|isbn=9789964303334|language=en}}</ref>
